Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (handles hardware/gesture back) and use `Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior` (handles the toolbar back button):

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            ConfirmDiscard();
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async void ConfirmDiscard()
    {
        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (discard)
        {
            _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, replace the default back arrow with a text button that routes through the same confirmation logic:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior Command="{Binding CancelCommand}"
                           TextOverride="Cancel" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then wire up the command:

```csharp
public EditProductPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = this;
    CancelCommand = new Command(OnCancelTapped);
}

public ICommand CancelCommand { get; }

private void OnCancelTapped()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        ConfirmDiscard();
    else
        Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles Android hardware back and swipe gestures.
- `BackButtonBehavior` with `TextOverride` replaces the toolbar arrow with "Cancel" and lets you intercept that tap via `Command`.
- Both paths funnel into `ConfirmDiscard()`, so the behavior is consistent.
